There are nine messages that can be displayed via “eye” glyphs. Four of these are in West parallel worlds, five in East worlds. Internally, the messages are placed in East, West, East, West, etc. in alternating order.

Note that the code that spawns the eyes is *not* a Lua script and cannot be extracted from the archive. It is built into the engine itself. The graphics are also not in the archive but are generated on the fly.

## Spawning details

The eye messages will be visible even if the game is saved and reloaded. A save with the eyes visible can be transferred to different computers, copied, and reloaded without issue.

* The eyes are only spawned once you cross over into an East or West biome area. **They will not appear until the “Entered East/West” message is triggered**, even if they would otherwise be visible.  
* The game will only spawn the eye messages in locations with the background “background\_cave\_02.png”. This includes some areas that do not *have* visible backgrounds, like some above-ground areas (notably EDR walls and the Lake area).  
* Every eye message, except the last one in East, has a corresponding message in the opposing parallel world. For example, if you find an eye message above East Lake, there will be one in the same place in West Lake. Note that they are *not the same message*, they’re just in the same locations across parallel worlds.  
* The eyes can spawn above or below ground. The reason they are often seen above the Lake or in the sky is simply because they’re more visible \-- underground, they blend into the background.  
* The actual spawning coordinate generation is unknown but appears to be based on the world seed.

**For the eyes to appear, the “mods\_have\_been\_active\_during\_this\_run” flag must not be set.** This doesn’t mean that you can’t use mods, the game just can’t know about it. Using mods, saving and quitting, and manually editing world\_state.xml will accomplish this (assuming you turned the mods off, of course). The eye messages will not be visible as long as the game thinks you have used mods during the run.

#### You can either patch the executable to remove the mod check, or use mods to get set up, and then disable mods and change the flag in world\_state.xml.

####  Patching the executable

Open noita.exe in a hex editor and go to offset 1af745. You'll see 0f 85 9d 01 00 00. replace that with 90 90 90 90 90 90\.

**These instructions are for the Feb 3, 2021 build of Noita and will not work with other versions.**

#### Changing the flag

Open the world\_state.xml file in C:\\Users\\(*username)*\\AppData\\LocalLow\\Nolla\_Games\_Noita\\save00\\world\_state.xml and change the line containing “mods\_have\_been\_active\_during\_this\_run="1"” to have a “0” instead.

Note that this will not allow you to have mods enabled \-- it will only make the game “forget” that you had mods on at all.

It’s also possible that the character set used is custom or otherwise expanded to allow for usage of the Finnish language.

### Stuff below here is probably old and not really useful

My interpretation is that the trigram format above is the correct way to “read” these, or at least close to the correct method. The below suggestions worked on creating digrams of two characters, which doesn’t work well when some messages have an odd number of characters.

### Polybius square

Given that the messages are composed of 5 unique characters, one possibility is a [Polybius square cipher](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polybius_square). However, some messages have an odd number of characters, which might imply this is the wrong path (or that some other condition applies).

Polybius squares typically combine I and J to give 25 letters, but some have been known to combine different characters (U/V, Q/Z, etc)

Initial thoughts:

* Given the layout in-game, it was originally thought characters were paired vertically (e.g. the first character from line 1 and 2 would be paired). However, at least one message has an odd number of lines, which throws a wrench in that.  
* As said, some messages have an odd number of characters, so that also throws a minor wrench into things.

### Playfair cipher

The [Playfair cipher](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Playfair_cipher) is related to the Polybius square but somewhat more complicated. It’s also slightly harder to brute force and requires keytext to go with the ciphertext, which we don’t have (yet).

* The playfair cipher works on pairs of digrams. In this case, some of the messages have an odd number of digrams, which isn’t compatible with this. More wrenches.
